quran[13]{c,v,t,f}:
36,28,"After him, We did not send down any hosts from the heaven; We stood in no need to send down any host."
36,29,"There was but a single Blast and suddenly they became silent and still. {1}",footnotes:1:These words contain a subtle satire. In their arrogance and pride of power and their strong antagonism towards the true faith
36,30,"Alas for My servants! Never does a Messenger come to them but they mock him."
36,31,"Have they not seen how many nations before them did We destroy? Thereafter they never came back to them. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
36,32,"All of them shall (one day) be gathered before Us."
36,33,"Let the {1} dead earth be a Sign for them. {2} We gave it life and produced from it grain whereof they eat.",footnotes:1:Until now the disbelieves of Makkah were being warned and reproved for their denial of the truth and their attitude of antagonism which they had adopted towards the Prophet (peace be upon him). Now the discourse turns to the basic thing which was the actual cause of the conflict between them and the Prophet (peace be upon him)
36,34,"We made in it gardens of date-palms and vines, and We caused springs to gush forth"
36,35,"that they might eat of its fruits. It was not their hands that made them. {1} Will they not, then, give thanks? {2}",footnotes:1:Another translation of this sentence can be: So that they may eat fruits thereof and what their own hands make. That is
36,36,"Holy is He {1} Who created all things in pairs, whether it be of what the earth produces, and of themselves, and of what they do not know. {2}",footnotes:1:This is still another argument for Tauhid. Here again certain realities of daily experience have been mentioned and it is suggested that man observes these day and night but does not ponder over them seriously
36,37,"And the night is another Sign for them. We strip the day from it and they become plunged in darkness. {1}",footnotes:1:The alternation of the night and day also is one of those realities which man does not regard as worthy of much attention only because it is a phenomenon of daily occurrence and experience; whereas if he considers how the day passes and how the night falls
36,38,"The sun is running its course to its appointed place. {1} That is the ordaining of the All-Mighty, the All-Knowing.",footnotes:1:“Place of rest” may either mean the place where the sun will ultimately come to a halt
36,39,"We have appointed stages for the moon till it returns in the shape of a dry old branch of palm-tree. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
36,40,"Neither does it lie in the sun's power to overtake the moon {1} nor can the night outstrip the day. {2} All glide along, each in its own orbit. {3}",footnotes:1:This sentence can have two meanings and both are correct.(1) The sun does not have the power that it should draw the moon into itself
